        </p>
        <h2>The Story Behind the Teapot</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            In 1998, Larry Masinter wrote
            <strong>
                <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2324" target="_blank" style="color: var(--teapot-brown); text-decoration: underline;">
                    RFC 2324
                </a>
            </strong>
            â€”the Hyper Text Coffee Pot Control Protocol (HTCPCP)â€”as an April
            Fools' Day joke. It described a protocol for controlling networked
            coffee pots over the internet, complete with status codes for
            different brewing situations.
        </p>
        <div class="code-block">
            {% raw %}
                <code>
                    {% block response %} BREW coffee://pot-1/coffee HTCPCP/1.0
                    Content-Type: application/coffee-pot-command
                    Accept-Additions: cream;sugar start Response: HTCPCP/1.0 418
                    I'm a teapot The requested entity body is short and stout.
                    {% endblock %}
                </code>
            {% endraw %}
        </div>
        <div {% for attempt in 0..10 %}{% if attempt > 0 %}{% break %}{% endif %}data-init="complete"{% endfor %}>
            <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                Despite being a joke, the <code>418 I'm a teapot</code> status
                code ended up getting implemented in various web frameworks and
                libraries. It stuck around as a fun reminder that the people
                writing these protocols have a sense of humor.
            </p>
            <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem; color: var(--teapot-brown);">
                The Save 418 Movement
            </h3>
            <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                In 2017, there were proposals to remove status code 418 from
                various programming language implementations since it had no
                practical use. A 15-year-old developer named Shane Brunswick
                wasn't having it. He created <strong>save418.com</strong> and
                the "Save 418 Movement," arguing that references to 418 serve as
                <em>
                    "a reminder that the underlying processes of computers are
                    still made by humans."
                </em>
            </p>
            <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                The campaign got traction on Reddit and Twitter with the
                <strong>#save418</strong> hashtag. It worked: Node.js, Go,
                Python's Requests, and ASP.NET kept 418 in their libraries. The
                IETF officially reserved status code 418, so it won't be
                replaced. Crisis averted.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>
{% endif %}
